## From Wireframes to Data Structures (LO1)

Following the finalization of my **"Skeuomorphic Passport"** design—a physical book metaphor featuring an Identity Page and a Visas Section—this week focused on the transition from visual UI to backend data architecture.

The primary goal was to create a **Data Definition Document (DDD)** that translates the "stamps" on the passport into a robust relational database. I realized that for the "Fandom Passport" to feel authentic, the data must be more than just a list of images; it needs to be a verifiable record of fan activity.

---

## Implementing the "Don't Repeat Yourself" (DRY) Principle (LO2)

Applying the principles from the Week 9 lecture, I moved away from a "flat" data structure to a normalized relational model.

### 1. Entity Relationship Mapping

To support the interaction where a user earns a stamp by completing a task, I designed a **Many-to-Many** relationship.

- **Users Table:** Stores the fan’s digital identity (ID, level, avatar)
- **Stamps Table:** A master catalog of all available visa stamps (concerts, album releases, voting events)
- **User_Stamps (Join Table):** Records which fan earned which stamp and the timestamp of issuance

---

### 2. Using SQL Joins for Dynamic UI

To render the "Right Page" of the passport, the system will use **SQL Joins** instead of hard-coded content.

- **Decision:** Use a `LEFT JOIN` between the `Stamps` table and the `User_Stamps` table  
- **Reasoning:** This allows the UI to display a 3x4 grid with empty slots for unearned stamps while showing filled icons for earned ones

This approach ensures that the interface reflects real-time user data rather than static design elements.

---

## Technical Evaluation: Scalability and Responsibility (LO3)

A key consideration this week was data integrity and scalability.

By using a relational database structure instead of storing all data within a single user object, the system becomes more flexible and easier to maintain.

For example, when a new album or event is released, only a single new record needs to be added to the `Stamps` table. This automatically makes it available for all users without modifying existing data.

This design also supports the use of **htmx** for dynamic updates, allowing the interface to render new stamps without reloading the entire page.

---

## Reflection

This week helped me understand that backend structure is not separate from interaction design. Instead, it directly shapes how the interface behaves and scales over time.

The combination of a skeuomorphic "passport" interface and a normalized relational backend creates a balance between emotional engagement and technical robustness.

This approach ensures that the system is not only visually compelling but also sustainable and extensible for future development.
